German Next-Year Electricity Advances as Coal Costs Increase

-- B y   L a r s   P a u l s s o n
-- 
2011-03-04T16:52:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/german-next-year-electricity-advances-as-coal-costs-increase.html
German electricity for delivery next
year gained for a second day in three as rising fuel prices
signaled more expensive generation costs for utilities in  Europe ’s biggest market.  Baseload power for 2012, the regional benchmark contract,
increased 65 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 53.60 euros ($74.74),
according to broker data compiled by Bloomberg at 5:20 p.m.
Berlin time. Baseload is delivered around the clock.  The contract had gained for a third week and has traded
from 50.75 euros to 54.60 euros this year. Last year it changed
hands from 48.80 euros to 58.35 euros.  Hard coal for next-year delivery to Amsterdam, Rotterdam or
Antwerp rose for a second day in three, gaining as much as 0.9
percent to $122.35 a metric ton. The fuel accounted for 18
percent of Germany’s power generation in 2009.  Germany  also
produces electricity from lignite, or brown coal, as well as
natural gas, nuclear, wind and solar plants.  Bloomberg tracks power prices from brokers including GFI
Group Inc., ICAP Plc, Spectron Group Ltd., Tradition and Tullet
Prebon Plc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Lars Paulsson in London at 
